    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.42-45_0001" />
                
                                                                                                                    <fw type="curatorial">42</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>Letters A C and banner</figDesc>
                        <p>A C <unclear>CEDIT <unclear/> CALAM</unclear></p>
                    </figure>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">
                        TELEPHONE
                            <lb/>
                        VICTORIA 3160 (6 LINES)
                            <lb/>
                        TELEGRAMS "AZYRITES, LONDON"
                        
                        
                        AUTHORS' CLUB,
                            <lb/>
                            2, WHITEHALL COURT, 
                                <lb/>
                                    S. W.
                    </hi>
                </fw>

                <opener>
                                                    <dateline>London, Dec. 24/12</dateline>


                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt: &#8212;</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Your kind words about my poem in <hi rend="underline"><title>Harper's Weekly</title></hi> was very heartening. I value them the more since they are the utterance of one who is himself a poet &#8212; whose work, <unclear>male</unclear>, dynamic and salient, I have long admired. Your lyre is a bard's lyre &#8212; no 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.42-45_0003"/>
                        
                    tinkling minor poet's mandolin.</p>
    
                <p>The first <unclear>book</unclear> of yours I read was lent me by my friend Phyllis Partington of California. It was a pleasant and peculiar coincidence that the same post which brought me your letter bore one for my wife &#8212; from "Mrs Bellman" of your city, accepting two poems of hers. Neither of us had ever received letters from Minneapolis before. Perhaps you may have noticed her work 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.42-45_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">43</fw>
                    
                    in some of the English and American magazines. She is one of England's <unclear>youngest</unclear> and most gifted poets.</p>
                
                <p>Your mention of <unclear>Yorse</unclear> recalls to my mind what he told me some time ago that no English or American magazine was edited by an accredited man of letters!</p>
    
                <p><title>"One Lyric Year"</title> is the more <unclear>hostile</unclear> and misrepresentative for not having something of yours. My own poem <unclear>they butchered</unclear> horribly in the composition.</p>
                
                <p>It is a <unclear>few minutes</unclear> of midnight &#8212; Christmas night. So here is wishing you a joyous one and a New Year pregnant with poetry &#8212; actual and transcribed. With many

                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.42-45_0004"/>
                                                                                                                                <fw type="curatorial">45</fw>

                    <unclear>Mantes</unclear> and Greetings,</p>
                <closer>
                                                            <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>

                                                            <signed>Herman Scheffauer</signed>

                                                            <note type="curatorial">[Scheffauer]</note> 


                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Bank Point</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Jackson's Lane,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Highgate, London.</addrLine>
                    
                            <addrLine>IV.</addrLine>  
                    </address>                       
                </closer>    
                
            </div1>
